sols:
The instantaneous rate of change of capital has two components:

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  We continuously add money at a rate of \$3,000 per year;
\item
  We earn 6\% interest compounded continuously.
\end{itemize}

If we denote by \emph{A(t)} the balance of the account at time \emph{t},
then we can write the differential equation

\begin{align*}
\frac{dA}{dt} &= 3000 + 6%\,A(t) \\
&= 3000 + 0.06\,A(t)\end{align*}

We solve this equation using separation of variables:

\begin{align*}\int \frac{dA}{3000+0.06A} = \int\,dt\end{align*}

Solving both sides separately yields

\begin{align*}\frac1{0.06} \ln|3000+0.06A| + C_1 = t + C_2\end{align*}

Since \emph{A} is positive, as the amount of money in the account, we
can drop the absolute value sign. This yields

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \ln(3000+0.06A) = 0.06t + C_3\end{align*}

or, equivalently

\begin{align*}3000 + 0.06A = e^{0.06t + C_3} = e^{0.06t}e^{C_3} = C_4 e^{0.06t}.\end{align*}

\emph{C\textsubscript{4}} is another arbitrary, but positive constant.
Hence we obtain for \emph{A(t)}:

\begin{align*}A(t) = \frac1{0.06}\left(C_4e^{0.06t}-3000\right).\end{align*}

Now it's time to think about the initial condition. Since the account
does not start with any balance initially, we know that \emph{A(0) = 0}.
This yields for \emph{C\textsubscript{4}} that

\begin{align*}0 = \frac1{0.06}\left(C_4e^{0}-3000\right), \quad \text{which implies} \quad C_4 = 3000.\end{align*}

With this we finally find the expression for the balance in dollars at
\emph{t} years:

\begin{align*}A(t) = \frac{3000}{0.06}\left(e^{0.06t}-1\right).\end{align*}

This implies that at \emph{t = 5} years the balance is

\begin{align*}A(5) = \frac{3000}{0.06}\left(e^{0.06\cdot 5}-1\right) = 17 492.94\end{align*}

\emph{Reality check:} Without interest we would expect to see \emph{5 x
3000 = 15 000} dollars in the account. The amount with interest should
be in the same order of magnitude and a little larger.
